Let $\mathbf{n} = \begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \\ c \end{pmatrix}$ be a normal vector to plane $P.$  Then the reflection of $\mathbf{n}$ across plane $P$ is $-\mathbf{n}.$

[asy]
import three;

size(180);
currentprojection = perspective(6,3,2);

triple I = (1,0,0), J = (0,1,0), K = (0,0,1), O = (0,-0.2,0);
triple N = (1,1,1), R = reflect((0,0,0),(N + reflect((0,0,0),N)*(N)) / 2)*(N);

draw(surface((2*I + 2*J)--(2*I - 2*J)--(-2*I - 2*J)--(-2*I + 2*J)--cycle),paleyellow,nolight);
draw((2*I + 2*J)--(2*I - 2*J)--(-2*I - 2*J)--(-2*I + 2*J)--cycle);
draw((2*I + 2*K)--(2*I - 2*K)--(-2*I - 2*K)--(-2*I + 2*K)--cycle);
draw((-2*J + 2*K)--(-2*J - 2*K)--(2*J - 2*K)--(2*J + 2*K)--cycle);
draw(O--N, Arrow3(6));
draw(O--R, Arrow3(6));
draw((0,0,0)--(0,0,1.2),dashed);

label("$\mathbf{n}$", N, N);
label("$-\mathbf{n}$", R, S);
label("$P$", (1,0,0), S);
[/asy]

Hence,
\[\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.5} \begin{pmatrix} \frac{11}{15} & \frac{2}{15} & \frac{2}{3} \\ \frac{2}{15} & \frac{14}{15} & -\frac{1}{3} \\ \frac{2}{3} & -\frac{1}{3} & -\frac{2}{3} \end{pmatrix} \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1} \begin{pmatrix} a \\ b \\ c \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -a \\ -b \\ -c \end{pmatrix}.\]This simplifies to
\[\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.5} \begin{pmatrix} 4a + 2b + 10c \\ 2a + 4b - 5c \\ 10a - 5b - 8c \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -15a \\ -15b \\ -15c \end{pmatrix}.\]Then $4a + 2b + 10c = -15a,$ $2a + 4b - 5c = -15b,$ and $10a - 5b - 8c = -15c.$  Solving, we find $a = 1,$ $b = 1,$ and $c = 2.$

Final Answer: $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}}.$ I hope it is correct.

